             <h2> Diets for athletes regarding Basket </h2>
        
        <p>
            Although basketball is a team sport, performance depends so much on group work
            <strong>(integration and interaction with other colleagues)</strong>
            as well as the individual qualities of the athlete.
            <br />
            <br />
        
           The nutritional requirements of the players depend on their position.
            The duration of a basketball game according to IBF
            <strong>(International Basketball Federation),</strong> it is four periods of 10 minutes each.
            <br />
            <br />
        Basketball players have to give the maximum in speed,
            strength, power, endurance and agility both in games and in specific training sessions.
           This game features a fast pace, a lot of skill and high intensity efforts,
            with variable payback periods,
            placing considerable demands on both aerobic and anaerobic energy systems.
            <br />
            <br />
        For this reason, basketball is considered a sport of mixed metabolic demand:
            the hour and a half game is considered aerobic work with interspersed periods
            of anaerobic actions.</p>
       
        <h3>Feeding in basket</h3>
        <p>
         You must consume enough carbohydrates and electrolytes before, during and after
            of matches / training to enhance performance and endurance.
            <br />
            <br />
        Try to eat at least three to four hours before a game,
            to increase energy reserves.
            Eat low glycemic carbohydrates such as<strong> oats, brown rice, quinoa, whole wheat pasta, artisan bread,</strong>
            to maximize your performance.
            Include lean protein and favorable fat in that meal, based on the plate rule.
            <br />
            <br />
       Avoid the<strong>simple carbohydrates</strong> qthat come from refined flours or sugars
            becouse <strong>those activate insulin</strong>, fat storage and inflammation
            thus increasing the risk of injury.</p>

